# Scope and Quality

## Only Touch What Was Asked

Only apply changes to the machine(s) or module(s) explicitly named in the task. Do not extend scope to other hosts. If a change seems relevant elsewhere, flag it verbally and ask — do not apply it unilaterally.

## No Unsolicited Changes

Do not add comments, refactor code, rename identifiers, reorganise files, or make any change not explicitly requested. Do not "improve" things that weren't mentioned. Before committing, run the de-slop skill to audit for AI artifacts (unnecessary comments, redundant docstrings, TODO leftovers).

## Investigate Before Fixing

When something is broken or behaving unexpectedly, investigate and explain the root cause before proposing a fix. Present your diagnosis to the user before acting. Do not apply workarounds that mask the underlying issue.

> "what's caused the stateVersion to be overridden. I don't think forcing it is the right idea. we should identify where it's set globally, remove it then set it in the machine config"

## Prefer the Simpler Solution

When multiple approaches exist, present the simpler one first. If you're adding abstraction, explain why the direct approach is insufficient. For NixOS module design, follow the dendritic pattern: prefer `imports` over enable options.
